<TITLE> EU says next Turkey govt must reinforce reform </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ANKARA, June 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The European Union said on Monday it expected Turkey's next government to press ahead with political reforms and said focusing on just the technical aspects of the accession process was not enough. Turkey will hold parliamentary elections on July 22, months ahead of schedule due to a political crisis that has pitted the Islamist-rooted government against the country's secular elite, which includes powerful army generals and top judges. "It is now important to have a new government that is able to reinforce the reform process and is able to bring Turkey still closer to the European Union," EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn told a news conference. Foreign Minister Abdullah Gul said reforms would continue. "This is not the Turkey of the 1960s and 1970s. We are an accession country. Political crises may occur but... the reform process will continue at full vigour," Gul said, dismissing suggestions the crisis may have changed Ankara's priorities. Turkey began accession talks in October 2005 but critics say reforms needed for Turkey to become a member of the bloc have slowed in the last two years amid disputes over Cyprus, human rights, judicial reform and other sensitive issues. Some put down the slow pace of implementation in some of these areas to resistance from a conservative establishment suspicious of the European Union. The bloc suspended discussions last December in eight of the 35 chapters, or policy areas, that it must work through due to Ankara's refusal to open its ports to EU member state Cyprus. Both the EU and Gul said they welcomed the fact that Turkey is set to open three new chapters later this month, but Rehn said this was not enough. "What really matters is the pace and intensity of reforms on the ground," Rehn sa
